Resonant control instability: a lightly damped mechanical mode (e.g., a flexible drive shaft or robot arm at ~30 Hz) is excited by the actuator, and its vibration couples back into the position/velocity sensor. If the control loop's bandwidth or sample rate overlaps that mode, the feedback amplifies it instead of damping it, producing limit-cycle oscillation or runaway. Aliasing makes it worse: vibration above Nyquist folds into the loop's passband and the controller "sees" a phantom low-frequency error it tries to correct. Classic example is a PID-driven servo on a compliant load where derivative gain amplifies sensor noise at the structural resonance, causing chatter and eventual gear or bearing damage. Mitigations include notch filters at the resonant frequency, lowering loop gain near that band, anti-alias filtering before the ADC, increasing structural damping, and gain-scheduling so the controller backs off when resonance is detected.
